{{Infobox ancient site|type = {{ill|Scallop Kofun|ja|帆立貝形古墳|12=draft|12=draft}} |name = Shiratorizuka Kofun |location = {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|Suzuka|ja|鈴鹿市|12=draft|12=draft}} Ueda-cho |coordinates = {{coord|34|54|05|N|136|31|34|E|region:JP-24_type:landmark_map_size:5000|display=inline,title}} |type = Scallop-shaped Kofun |area = Total length 80m, height 13m |built = Early 5th century |burial goods = Cylindrical haniwa |alternate_name = Mie Prefecture Historic Site (Historic Site1 in {{ill|Showa|ja|昭和|12=draft|12=draft}} 12 (1937))<ref>{{Cite web|title=白鳥塚古墳|url=http://www.bunka.pref.mie.lg.jp/bunkazai/da/item/detail.asp?spetype=11&prePageNum=2&mngnum=0000166|publisher=Mie Prefectural Board of Education|accessdate=2012-08-05}}</ref> |image = [[File:Shiratoriduka Kohun.JPG|250px]] }}
[[File:Shiratoriduka Kohun2.JPG|250px|right|thumb|Pathway Entrance]]
'''Shiratorizuka Kofun''' (白鳥塚古墳) is the main tumulus of the Shiratorizuka Kofun Group, which consists of seven tumuli, located in {{ill|Suzuka|ja|鈴鹿市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is officially named '''Shiratorizuka Kofun No. 1''' and is the largest scallop-shaped kofun in Mie Prefecture.
== Overview ==
The kofun derives its name, "Shiratorizuka," from the {{ill|Yamato Takeru|ja|ヤマトタケル|12=draft|12=draft}}'s White Bird Legend. It is also known by various names such as Hiyodorizuka, Chausuyama, and Maruyama.
Many late {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft|12=draft}} kokugaku scholars, including {{ill|Motoori Norinaga|ja|本居宣長|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref>Motoori Norinaga's ''{{ill|Kojikiden|ja|古事記伝|12=draft|12=draft}}'' identified Shiratorizuka as the most likely candidate for the Nobono tomb described in the ''Kojiki''.</ref> and {{ill|Hirata Atsutane|ja|平田篤胤|12=draft|12=draft}}, regarded Shiratorizuka as the most plausible site for the Nobono Tomb (能褒野陵墓) of Yamato Takeru as described in the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft|12=draft}}.
In {{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|12=draft|12=draft}} 9 (1876), the Ministry of Religious Affairs Historic Site1 Shiratorizuka as Yamato Takeru's tomb. However, this decision was overturned by the Imperial Household Ministry in Meiji 12 (1879), which instead Historic Site1 {{ill|Chōjizuka|ja|丁子塚|12=draft|12=draft}} (now in {{ill|Kameyama, Mie|ja|亀山市|12=draft|12=draft}}) as Yamato Takeru's tomb, currently recognized as the {{ill|Nobono Ōtsuka Kofun|ja|能褒野王塚古墳|12=draft|12=draft}}.
A scholarly survey conducted between {{ill|Heisei|ja|平成|12=draft|12=draft}} 16 (2004) and 17 (2005) confirmed that Shiratorizuka, historically considered a circular kofun, is actually scallop-shaped.
== burial ==
* Total length: 78 meters * Rear circular mound diameter: 67 meters, height: 9 meters * Front rectangular mound length: 16.4 meters, width: 27 meters * The mound features a two-tiered structure with a base plattype. * Based on its design, the kofun is believed to have been constructed in the early 5th century.
== burial goods ==
Due to degradation caused by medieval conflicts, the only burial goods confirmed during the academic survey from Heisei 16 to 17 were multiple cylindrical {{ill|haniwa|ja|埴輪|12=draft|12=draft}}. Reports from the early Meiji period suggest the discovery of a stone chamber, though its existence has not been verified.
== location ==
* {{ill|Suzuka|ja|鈴鹿市|12=draft|12=draft}} Ueda-cho, Mie Prefecture
== Access ==
* Approximately 30 minutes on foot from {{ill|Kasado Station|ja|加佐登駅|12=draft|12=draft}} on the {{ill|Kansai Main Line|ja|関西線 (名古屋地区)|12=draft|12=draft}} operated by JR.
== Nearby Sites ==
* {{ill|Kasado Shrine|ja|加佐登神社|12=draft|12=draft}} - A shrine dedicated to Yamato Takeru no Mikoto.
== References == {{Reflist}} {{Footnotes Help}}
== Sources == * ''Suzuka City History'' (鈴鹿市史), compiled by Suzuka City.
== Related Articles == * {{ill|Nobono Ōtsuka Kofun|ja|能褒野王塚古墳|12=draft|12=draft}}
== External Links == * [http://www.edu.city.suzuka.mie.jp/museum/shiratori-gen.pdf Shiratorizuka Kofun Excavation Data]
